---

<Layout>
  <main class="container">
    <h1 class="margin-start-m">Introduction to HTML</h1>

    <p>
      HTML stands for <strong>Hypertext Markup Language</strong>. It was
      publicly released in October 1991 by Tim Berners-Lee as a foundational
      language of the World Wide Web.
    </p>
    <p>
      As the standard for creating web pages using Hypertext (the concept of
      linking 'text' documents together to create associations between them),
      HTML offers perhaps the most robust, open and accessible way to structure
      and author digital content.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a target="_blank" href="https://resilientwebdesign.com/"
          >Read 'Resilient Web Design' by Jeremy Keith</a
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <a target="_blank" href="https://thehistoryoftheweb.com/timeline/"
          >Discover the history of the web</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      HTML is considered a <strong>declarative language</strong> used primarily in
      <strong>front-end</strong> web development.
    </p>

    <h2>Declarative vs. Imperative</h2>

    <dl class="margin-start-m callout outline">
      <dt>Declarative Languages</dt>
      <dd>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Describe your desired result rather than outlining each step the
            computer should take to reach it.
          </li>
          <li><strong>What</strong>, not <strong>how</strong>.</li>
          <li>Examples: HTML, CSS, SQL.</li>
        </ul>
      </dd>

      <dt>Imperative Languages</dt>
      <dd>
        <ul>
          <li>Create a step-by-step process for how a program runs.</li>
          <li>
            Use individual statements, instructions and methods to create a
            control flow.
          </li>
          <li>Examples: Java, JavaScript (mostly), Ruby, PHP, C.</li>
        </ul>
      </dd>
    </dl>

    <h2>Front end vs. Back end</h2>

    <dl class="margin-start-m callout outline">
      <dt>Front end (client side)</dt>
      <dd>
        Focuses on visible, user-facing aspects of a website<br />
        <em>HTML, CSS, JavaScript (and its many offshoots)</em>
        <ul>
          <li>Layout</li>
          <li>UI/UX Design</li>
          <li>Interaction</li>
          <li>Media (images, videos, SVGs)</li>
          <li>Accessibility</li>
        </ul>
      </dd>
      <dt>Back end (server side)</dt>
      <dd>
        Focuses on hidden, server-side parts of a website<br />
        <em>PHP, Node (JavaScript), SQL, Python, Ruby, Java</em>
        <ul>
          <li>Application logic</li>
          <li>Database management</li>
          <li>Server architecture</li>
          <li>APIs</li>
        </ul>
      </dd>
    </dl>

    <h2>Front-end languages</h2>
    <dl>
      <dt>HTML</dt>
      <dd>
        Gives a webpage content and structure. Uses elements within tags to
        define different types of content.
        <Code
          class="margin-start-m"
          code={`<h1 class="hello-world">Hello World!</h1>;`}
          lang="html"
        />
      </dd>

      <dt>CSS</dt>
      <dd>
        Alters a webpage's style and design. Uses selectors to target HTML
        elements and assign them style properties and values.
        <br />
        <Code
          class="margin-start-m"
          code={`h1.hello-world { color: rebeccapurple; }`}
          lang="css"
        />
      </dd>

      <dt>JavaScript</dt>
      <dd>
        Adds Logic and Interactivity to a webpage. Uses variables and functions
        to create a more dynamic experience where content can be updated and
        changed through user interaction.
        <br />

        <Code
          class="margin-start-m"
          code={`document.addEventListener("click", (event) => {
	alert("Alert World!")
});`}
          lang="js"
        />
      </dd>
    </dl>

    <h2>Where do I write my code?</h2>
    <p>
      Code can be written almost anywhere! You just need to save it with the
      correct file extension (e.g. .html for HTML files). However, a code editor
      will make your life much easier, with features like syntax highlighting,
      auto-completion, and error detection. Code editors with many features are
      often referred to as Integrated Development Environments (IDEs). Here are
      some popular code editors:
    </p>

    <ul class="margin-start-m">
      <li>
        <a target="_blank" href="https://code.visualstudio.com/"
          >Visual Studio Code</a
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <a target="_blank" href="https://www.jetbrains.com/webstorm/"
          >WebStorm (JetBrains)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <a target="_blank" href="https://notepad-plus-plus.org/">Notepad++</a>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Let's get started!</h2>

    <div class="breakout">
      <Sandpack
        client:load
        files={{
          "/index.html":
`<!DOCTYPE html> 
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
    <title>My First HTML Page</title>
  </head>

  <body>
    <!-- This is an HTML comment.
    It doesn't appear on the webpage, only in the code itself.
    We will be using these to explain the code. -->
    <h1>This is the first heading on the page.</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph.</p>
  </body>
</html>`,
        }}
        template="static"
        theme="dark"
        options={{ showLineNumbers: true }}
      />
    </div>

    <p class="margin-start-m">
      Notice how HTML elements are nested within each other? They can have
      parent, child or sibling relationships. This gives our web page a
      meaningful structure. We can also reference these relationships in our CSS
      and JS to target specific elements.
    </p>
    <p>
      The indentation is optional and is only done for readability. Some people
      indent 2 spaces, some 4. Sometimes tabs are used, sometimes spaces. This
      is not at all a source of immense conflict between developers.
    </p>

    <div class="callout outline primary margin-start-m">
      <h2>Let's try it out!</h2>
      <p>
        If you have the local files for this workshop website, open: <br /><Code
          code="playgrounds/html-1/index.html"
          lang="html"
          inline
        /> or create your own <Code code="index.html" lang="html" inline /> file.
      </p>
      <a
        href="../playgrounds/html-1/index.html"
        target="_blank"
        class="primary subtle margin-start-m block">View Playground</a
      >
    </div>

    <div class="callout outline margin-start-m">
      <h3>Doctype declaration</h3>
      <p>
        The <Code code="<!DOCTYPE html>" lang="html" inline /> element at the top
        is called the Doctype Declaration. This is only used once, right at the top
        of the page.
      </p>
      <p>
        This version of the declaration tells web browsers that this document is
        written in the standard of HTML5 and above, so the browser knows how to
        display it correctly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout outline margin-start-m">
      <h3>HTML tag</h3>
      <p>
        The Doctype Declaration is followed by an <Code
          code="<html>"
          lang="html"
          inline
        /> opening tag which marks where your HTML starts. The last tag on the page
        should be the <Code code="<html>" lang="html" inline /> closing tag, to close
        out the document.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout outline margin-start-m">
      <h3>Head tag</h3>
      <p>
        The <Code code="<html>" lang="html" inline /> tag is then followed by a <Code
          code="<head>"
          lang="html"
          inline
        /> tag.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <Code code="<head>" lang="html" inline /> section contains information
        for web browsers and search engines, such as the page title, links to CSS
        stylesheets and JavaScript files, metadata, and display settings.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout outline margin-start-m">
      <h3>Body tag</h3>
      <p>
        The <Code code={`<head>`} lang="html" inline /> is followed by the <Code
          code={`<body>`}
          lang="html"
          inline
        /> tag. This is where all the visible content for your webpage will go.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="breakout margin-start-m">
      <Sandpack
        client:load
        files={{
          "/index.html": `<!DOCTYPE html> 
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
    <title>My First HTML Page</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Heading 1</h1>
    <h2>Heading 2</h2>
    <h3>Heading 3</h3>
    <h4>Heading 4</h4>
    <h5>Heading 5</h5>
    <h6>Heading 6</h6>
    <p>Paragraph text.</p>
  </body>
</html>`,
        }}
        template="static"
        theme="dark"
        options={{ showLineNumbers: true }}
      />
    </div>

    <p class="margin-start-m">
      Let's take a look at the heading sizes on the webpage. Notice that the
      browser already has some basic default styles to differentiate the
      headings.
    </p>

    <p>
      Ideally, we should use only one <Code code="<h1>" lang="html" inline /> element
      per page. This is the top-level heading; everything else is second to it.
    </p>

    <ul class="margin-start-m">
      <li>
        Make sure you're following the heading hierarchy. Using
        <Code code="<h3>" lang="html" inline /> for subheadings, then
        <Code code="<h2>" lang="html" inline /> for sub-subheadings, would look weird.
      </li>
      <li>
        Try not to use more than 3 heading levels if you can. If you're creating
        a super deep hierarchy, it's probably a sign some of your content should
        be on a different page!
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Adding CSS and JavaScript</h2>
    <p>
      Our HTML file is now ready to use, but ot will look very plain without any
      CSS styling and it won't be very interactive without any JavaScript
      (although that might be a good thing - JS is not always necessary for a
      good web page). There are a few ways we can add other types of code to our
      HTML:
    </p>

    <div class="callout outline margin-start-m">
      <h3>Inline</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Writing code directly into our HTML elements - often as an attribute.
        </li>
        <li>
          Can be difficult to make and track adjustments if your page has a lot
          of content.
        </li>
        <li>Not ideal for code readability.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="breakout margin-start-m">
      <Sandpack
        client:load
        files={{
          "/index.html": `<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
    <title>Inline Examples</title>
  </head>

  <body>
    <!-- Here's an inline style -->
    <h1 style="color:purple;">This is a purple heading</h1>
       
    <!-- Here's an inline script on a button element -->
    <button onclick="alert('Alert JavaScript!');">Click me to alert!</button>

    <button id="alertButton">Click me to log to the console!</button>
          
    <!-- Here's an inline script within the body -->
    <script>
      const alertButton = document.querySelector("#alertButton");
      alertButton.addEventListener("click", (e) => {
        console.log('Logged to the console!');
      });
    </script>

  </body>
</html>`,
        }}
        template="static"
        theme="dark"
        options={{ showLineNumbers: true, showConsole: true }}
      />
    </div>

    <div class="callout outline margin-start-m">
      <h3>Internal</h3>

      <p>Add code between our <Code code="<head>" lang="html" inline /> tags</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Use <Code code="<style>" lang="html" inline /> tags for CSS</li>
        <li>Use <Code code="<script>" lang="html" inline /> tags for JS</li>
        <li>Useful if styling a single page</li>
        <li>Can get tricky to manage if more pages are added</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <Code
      class="margin-start-m"
      code={`<head>
   <!-- Here's an internal style in the head -->
   <style>
    body {background-color: powderblue;} 
    h1 {color: blue;}
    p {color: red;}
  </style>

  <!-- Here's an internal script in the head -->
  <script>
    document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = "Hello JavaScript!";
  </script>
</head>`}
      lang="html"
    />

    <div class="callout outline margin-start-m">
      <h3>External</h3>

      <ul>
        <li>Imports styles and scripts from separate .css and .js files</li>
        <li>Helps keep HTML readable</li>
        <li>Easy to make changes</li>
        <li>Can be referenced on multiple webpages - great for consistency!</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="margin-start-m">
      <h3>Importing external resources</h3>

      <kelp-tabs>
        <ul class="list-inline" tabs>
          <li><a href="#same-folder">Same Folder</a></li>
          <li><a href="#sibling-folder">Sibling Folder</a></li>
          <li><a href="#external-resource">External Resource</a></li>
        </ul>

        <div id="same-folder">
          <p>
            When your CSS and JS files are in the same folder as your HTML file,
            you can link to them directly by their filename.
          </p>

            <Code
            class="margin-start-m"
            code={
`<head>
  <!-- Here's how to import an external style -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">

  <!-- Here's how to import an external script -->
  <script src="script.js" defer></script>
</head>`}
            lang="html"
            />
        </div>

        <div id="sibling-folder">
          <p>Navigate up and down the folder structure using ../</p>
          <Code
            class="margin-start-m"
            code={
`<head>
  <!-- Here's how to import an external style -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="../assets/styles.css">

  <!-- Here's how to import an external script -->
  <script src="../assets/script.js" defer></script>
</head>`}
            lang="html"
          />
        </div>

        <div id="external-resource">
          <p>
            Reference external resources using their full URL. This is called an
            absolute URL.
          </p>
            <Code
            class="margin-start-m"
            code={
`<head>
  <!-- Here's how to import an external style -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://my-external-resource.com/styles.css">

  <!-- Here's how to import an external script -->
  <script src="https://my-external-resource.com/script.js" defer></script>
</head>`}
            lang="html"
            />
        </div>
      </kelp-tabs>
    </div>
  
      <h2>Common HTML tags</h2>

      <div class="breakout margin-start-m">
        <Sandpack
          client:load
          files={{
            "/index.html":
`<!DOCTYPE html>
