          }}
          template="static"
          theme="dark"
          options={{ showLineNumbers: true }}
        />
      </div>

      <h2 class="margin-start-m">Using alt text for images</h2>
      <p>Alt text is a tool used by screen readers to describe an image to those with impaired vision.</p>
<Code
  class="margin-start-m"
  code={
`<section id="my-cat">
  <h1>Look at my cat!!!!</h1>
  <img src="images/cat.jpg" alt="black and white cat" width="640" height="480">
</section>`}
  lang="html"
/>

      <ul class="margin-start-m">
        <li>
          It's in our best interests to make our page as accessible as we can so we should always be adding alt text to our
          <Code code="<img>" lang="html" inline /> elements!
        </li>
        <li>
          Alt text is an attribute, so we will add it to our tag after our source attribute.
        </li>
        <li>
          Describe the image without referring to it as an image: for example, write 'a brown dog' instead of 'a picture of a brown dog'.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <Code
        class="margin-start-m"
        code={
`<body>
  <!-- Modern HTML has semantic tags for areas of your page -->
  <header>This could be the header of the whole page or just part of the page</header>

  <main>
  <!-- This is the main content of the webpage. 
  Usually there is only one <main> element per page. -->

  <article>This is an article within the main content.</article>
  <section>This is a section within the main content.</section>
  <aside>This is an aside within the main content.</aside>

  <div>
    <p>Wrapped around this paragraph is the much used and much maligned div tag! It's useful for containing and grouping content when it doesn't make sense to use any of the other semantic tags. Use it as little as possible!</p>
  </div>

  </main>

  <footer>This is the footer of the whole page or part of the page.</footer>

</body>`}
        lang="html"
      />

      <h2>HTML attributes</h2>

      <p>We talked a bit about attributes earlier: they are extra information we add into the opening tag of an element.</p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          Attributes consist of two parts:
          <ul>
            <li>Name (e.g. <Code code="class" lang="html" inline />)</li>
            <li>
              Value (e.g. <Code code="heading-bold" lang="html" inline />)
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
          One commonly used attribute is ID. We can use ID to pick out specific elements, and is useful if you're using an element more than once.
        </li>
        <li>
          Attributes like class and id become incredibly useful once we start styling in CSS, as we can use these to apply unique style rules to a single element.
        </li>
        <li>
          While you can reuse classes on as many elements as you wish, No two HTML elements should share the same ID, so get inventive with your IDs!
        </li>
      </ul>

      <Code
        class="margin-start-m"
        code={
`<body>
  <!-- Here's are some attributes on an h1 tag -->
  <h1 class="heading-bold" id="main-heading">This is the main heading</h1>
</body>`}
        lang="html"
      />

      <h2>Semantic HTML</h2>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Semantic adj. se.man.tic </em><br>
        1. of or relating to meaning of language.<br>
        2. of or relating to Semantics, the study of the meaning of language.
      </blockquote>

      <h3>Why do we need semantic HTML?</h3>

      <p>Semantic HTML uses tags which best convey the underlying meaning of the content the tag contains. There are two big reasons this is important:</p>

      <h4>Accessibility</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>
          As we saw earlier, semantically accurate HTML makes it much easier to convey what you mean to those who use a screen reader.
        </li>
        <li>
          Semantics also comes into play when we're considering whether a page is accessible for neurodivergent users.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Readability</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>
          If your page is laid out illogically, people won't take the time to read it. Modern users have a good eye, and will lose interest if they can't find the info they want.
        </li>
        <li>
          Semantic cohesion plays a role in Search Engine Optimisation (SEO).
        </li>
        <li>
          Your HTML code needs to be easy to understand for other developers maintaining it!
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>HTML nesting</h3>

      <p>Here, we've used the section tag to create containers for our content.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>We have then nested groups of semantically-related content within these containers.</li>
        <li>This structure will be easier for screen readers, search engines, and other developers to comprehend.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout outline margin-start-m">
        <h3>Choosing the right element</h3>

        <p><Code code="<div>" lang="html" inline /></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Used to group content that is not semantically related.</li>
          <li>Meaningless to screen readers.</li>
          <li>Mainly used for grouping content for CSS targeting - a style container for other elements.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p><Code code="<section>" lang="html" inline /></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Applied to content that can be grouped together in a semantically meaningful way.</li>
          <li>Grouped content in a <Code code="<section>" lang="html" inline /> should have a 'theme' - often declared with a heading.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><Code code="<article>" lang="html" inline /></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Most specific container.</li>
          <li>Groups content that is semantically related and self-contained; it can be isolated from the rest of the page and still make sense.</li>
          <li>E.g. - a recipe from a food blog.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h3 class="margin-start-m">
        Combining elements to create meaningful structure
      </h3>

      <Code
        class="margin-start-m"
        code={
`<section>
  <h1>Latest Recipe posts</h1>

  <article>
    <h2>Gluten-Free Chocolate Muffins</h2>
    <p>These triple chocolate muffins will light up any special occasion.</p>
  </article>

  <article>
    <h2>Pork and Chive Baozi</h2>
    <p>Tasty filling with soft, fluffy wrappers, homemade bao buns are super comforting!</p>
  </article>
  
</section>`}
        lang="html"
      />

      <p class="margin-start-m">Now you have the basics of HTML try marking up a web page: focus on structure rather than style.</p>

      <p><a
          href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Reference/Elements"
          target="_blank"
          >HTML Elements Reference on MDN: All the HTML things!</a
        ></p>
  </main>
</Layout>

